UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 392/GA
1 AN ACT relating to local public agency transactions.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 45A.385 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) The local public agency may use small purchase procedures for any contract for
5 which a determination is made that the aggregate amount of the contract does not
6 exceed fifty thousand dollars ($50,000)[forty thousand dollars ($40,000)] if small
7 purchase procedures are in writing and available to the public.
8 (2) Beginning in calendar year 2030, the small purchase maximum amount set out in
9 subsection (1) of this section shall be increased by ten thousand dollars ($10,000)
10 every five (5) years effective on January 1 of each year. The Finance and
11 Administration Cabinet shall, through a technical advice memorandum or other
12 official means of communication, announce the small purchase maximum
13 amount in effect for the current year, and shall also prominently post that
14 information on its website.
15 Section 2. KRS 45A.420 is amended to read as follows:
16 (1) Any local public agency may enter into an agreement for cooperative purchasing
17 with any other local public agency. When the contracting local public agency
18 contracts for supplies, services or construction pursuant to KRS 45A.365, 45A.370,
19 45A.375, or 45A.380, all other parties to the agreement shall be deemed to have
20 complied with the provisions of those sections.
21 (2) Nothing in KRS 45A.345 to 45A.990 shall deprive a local public agency from
22 negotiating with vendors for supplies where such supplies are the subject of a price
23 agreement with the Commonwealth of Kentucky provided, however, that no
24 contract executed under this section would authorize a price higher than is
25 contained in the price agreement with the Commonwealth of Kentucky for such
26 specific supplies.
27 (3) For agreements that do not establish a fixed unit price, a local public agency may
Page 1 of 8
HB039210.100 - 1684 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:19 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 392/GA
1 make purchases using an established discount, quote, formula, or other pricing
2 method as established by the Commonwealth in the agreement. A local public
3 agency shall retain records documenting its compliance with the procedures
4 required in the applicable agreement.
5 (4)[(3)] Nothing in KRS 45A.345 to 45A.990 shall deprive a local school district from
6 acquiring supplies outside of price agreements with the Commonwealth of
7 Kentucky if the supplies meet the same specifications as the contract items and the
8 supplies are purchased at a lower price than is contained in the price agreement with
9 the Commonwealth of Kentucky for such specific supplies and the purchase does
10 not exceed two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500).
11 Section 3. KRS 82.083 is amended to read as follows:
12 (1) As used in this section, "independent appraisal" means an appraisal made by:
13 (a) An individual or organization not affiliated with the city or its officers or
14 employees, using a generally accepted national or professional standard; or
15 (b) A city's officers or employees using:
16 1. A nationally published valuation of property based on the most recent
17 edition of the publication; or
18 2. For personal property with no applicable nationally published
19 valuation standard, a generally accepted method to determine a good-
20 faith estimate of the value of the personal property.
21 (2) A city may sell or otherwise dispose of any of its real or personal property.
22 (3) Before selling or otherwise disposing of any real or personal property that has any
23 value, the city shall make a written determination setting forth and fully describing:
24 (a) The real or personal property;
25 (b) Its intended use at the time of acquisition;
26 (c) The reasons why it is in the public interest to dispose of it;[ and]
27 (d) The method used to estimate value when the property is personal property
Page 2 of 8
HB039210.100 - 1684 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:19 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 392/GA
1 appraised under subsection (1)(b)2. of this section; and
2 (e) The method of disposition to be used.
3 (4) Real or personal property may be:
4 (a) Transferred, with or without compensation, to another governmental agency;
5 (b) Transferred, with or without compensation, for economic development
6 purposes, which shall include but not be limited to real property transfers for
7 the elimination of blight;
8 (c) Sold at public auction following publication of the auction in accordance with
9 KRS 424.130(1)(b);
10 (d) Sold by electronic auction following publication of the auction, including the
11 uniform resource link (URL) for the site of the electronic auction, in
12 accordance with KRS 424.130(1)(b);
13 (e) Sold by sealed bids in accordance with the procedure for sealed bids under
14 KRS 45A.365(3) and (4);
15 (f) Traded towards the purchase of the same or similar type of property, if the
16 trade-in value received equals or exceeds the actual fair market value of the
17 property as determined using an independent appraisal as defined in
18 subsection (1) of this section;
19 (g) Sold for its appraised fair market value or a greater amount if the property is
20 valued at ten thousand dollars ($10,000) or less in an independent appraisal.
21 Property sold under this paragraph may not be sold to a city officer or
22 employee or family member of a city officer or employee as defined in the
23 city's ethics ordinance adopted under KRS 65.003;
24 (h) Notwithstanding subsection (3) of this section, sold for scrap or disposed of as
25 garbage in a manner consistent with the public interest if the property has no
26 value, or is of negligible value as determined by an independent appraisal;
27 (i) Sold by the Finance and Administration Cabinet under an agreement with the
Page 3 of 8
HB039210.100 - 1684 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:19 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 392/GA
1 city; or
2 (j) Notwithstanding subsection (3) of this section, when the property is an animal
3 used in service by the city, given to the animal's primary handler or trainer,
4 without the payment of compensation, when the animal is retired or is no
5 longer capable of performing service to the city.
6 (5) If a city receives no bids for the real or personal property, either at public or
7 electronic auction or by sealed bid, the property may be disposed of, consistent with
8 the public interest, in any manner deemed appropriate by the city. In those
9 instances, a written description of the property, the method of disposal, and the
10 amount of compensation, if any, shall be made.
11 (6) Any compensation resulting from the disposal of this real or personal property shall
12 be transferred to the general fund of the city.
13 Section 4. KRS 82.084 is amended to read as follows:
14 KRS 45A.345 to 45A.460 and 424.260 shall not apply to city governments, urban-county
15 governments, consolidated local governments, or air boards identified in and operating
16 under the provisions of KRS 183.142(1) for the purchase of:
17 (1) Products or services when there is a single source of the product or service to be
18 procured within a reasonable geographic area;
19 (2) Products needed as replacement parts for personal property or equipment where the
20 need cannot be reasonably anticipated and maintaining an inventory of replacement
21 parts is not feasible;[ and]
22 (3) Vehicles and equipment installed on vehicles that are used exclusively for law
23 enforcement purposes, if the purchaser obtains at least three (3) quotes prior to
24 making the purchase and retains records documenting the quotes; and
25 (4) Products or services that are provided by:
26 (a) Entities recognized by the Office of Vocational Rehabilitation under KRS
27 Chapter 163 that operate programs for the rehabilitation of individuals who
Page 4 of 8
HB039210.100 - 1684 - XXXX 2/18/2026 2:19 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 392/GA
1 are blind or visually impaired;
2 (b) Agencies for individuals with severe disabilities as described in KRS
3 45A.465;
4 (c) A qualified veterans' workshop providing job and employment-skill training
5 to veterans where such a workshop is operated by the United States
6 Department of Veterans Affairs;
7 (d) Nonprofit organizations, employment services organizations, or other private
8 business organizations with established operations within the jurisdiction of
9 the city, urban-county government, or consolidated local government with the
10 main mission or business purpose of serving individuals with disabilities by
11 offering transitional or supported employment services or other rehabilitative
12 programs and services, including but not limited to serving individuals with
13 severe mental or physical disabilities or those recovering from substance
14 abuse disorders; or
15 (e) Nonprofit community service organizations operating within the jurisdiction
16 of the city, urban-county government, or consolidated local government when
17 there is a determination in the official record of the legislative body that the
18 purchase of the products or services would serve a mutual benefit to the
19 government and the organization by:
20 1. Furthering the purposes of the organization;
21 2. Providing a service or product needed by the government;
22 3. Advancing a specific public purpose; and
23 4. Serving the best interest of the public.
24 If two (2) or more organizations meet the qualifications set out in this
25 paragraph, then the government shall award the contract to one (1) of the
26 qualifying organizations using the selection criteria of its adopted competitive
27 bidding process.
